<h1>LG Dryer Not Drying Clothes — Why It Takes Too Long and How We Fix It</h1>

<p>A dryer that takes two or three cycles to dry a normal load is one of the most frustrating appliance problems — and one of the most common calls we get after "no heat." LG dryers should dry a full load in 45–60 minutes on normal heat settings. When you're routinely running 90-minute cycles or throwing loads in twice, something is wrong. The difference between this and a complete no-heat failure is important: the dryer has heat, but not enough of it, or the airflow isn't moving that heat through the drum correctly. We see these calls constantly across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County — and in most cases the fix is faster and cheaper than people expect.</p>

<h2>The Most Likely Causes — In Order</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    1. Clogged Exhaust Vent
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Most common — 70% of calls</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Clothes come out hot but damp</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">d80 / d90 / d95 error codes</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Laundry room gets humid while running</div>
  </div>
  <p>The exhaust vent removes hot moist air from the drum — if it's clogged with lint, the humid air has nowhere to go. The dryer runs hot but moisture stays trapped with your clothes. You'll feel it: the outside of the dryer gets unusually warm, the laundry room gets humid, and the exterior vent flap barely moves when the dryer runs. LG displays d80, d90, or d95 error codes when sensors detect 80–95% blockage. In Pasadena and Glendale, where older homes often have longer vent runs with more bends, we find blockages more often than anywhere else. We use a digital manometer to measure back-pressure in the vent system — not guesswork, actual airflow numbers. Don't ignore the d-codes — a fully clogged vent will eventually blow the thermal fuse and turn your slow-drying problem into a complete no-heat failure.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    2. Partially Failed Heating Element (Electric Dryers)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Electric dryers only</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Weak heat — not zero heat</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Gets worse gradually over weeks</div>
  </div>
  <p>A heating element with a break in one section still produces heat — just not enough. The dryer runs warm rather than hot. A normal load takes 80–90 minutes instead of 45. We see this frequently on 8–12 year old DLEX and DLE series. The progression is gradual: first loads take a bit longer, then you're running two cycles routinely, then one day the element fails completely. On DLEX models the element is easily accessible from the rear. On DLGX units we need to remove the front panel to reach it. We test for continuity and correct resistance — a partial break shows clearly on a multimeter. Cost: $300–380. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-heating-element-replacement/">heating element replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    3. Moisture Sensor Needs Cleaning
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Very common — often overlooked</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Auto-dry cycles end too early</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Timed dry works fine, auto-dry doesn't</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Dryer sheet residue on sensor bars</div>
  </div>
  <p>This one surprises people every time. LG dryers use metal sensor bars inside the drum to detect when clothes are dry. When these bars get coated with dryer sheet residue — which happens with regular use — they read "dry" before the clothes actually are. The cycle ends early, clothes come out damp, and everyone assumes there's a heating problem. There isn't. We clean the sensor bars on every slow-drying call as part of the diagnostic. If the problem goes away, you've saved yourself an unnecessary repair. We also show you how to clean them yourself every few months — it's a 2-minute task with a cotton ball and rubbing alcohol. Quick test you can do before calling us: switch from auto-dry to a timed 60-minute cycle. If clothes come out dry that way, the sensor is the issue, not the heating system.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    4. Worn Drum Rollers or Slipping Belt
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Less common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Clothes bunched — not tumbling evenly</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Center of load stays damp</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Sometimes a squeaking noise</div>
  </div>
  <p>If the drum isn't tumbling clothes properly — because of worn <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-drum-roller-replacement/">drum rollers</a> or a slipping belt — clothes don't move evenly through the heated airstream. Items in the center stay damp while things near the outside dry fine. The dryer is hot enough, but the mechanical tumbling isn't doing its job. We check drum rotation and roller condition on every slow-dry call. Cost: $280–350 for roller replacement.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    5. Gas Valve Coils Failing Intermittently (Gas Dryers)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Gas dryers only</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Gas dryers only</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Works sometimes, not others</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Progressively getting worse</div>
  </div>
  <p>Gas valve solenoid coils that are failing intermittently cause the burner to light sometimes and not others. The dryer heats for one cycle, runs cold the next. Over time the coils weaken further and the burner fires less and less frequently per cycle. Clothes take longer because the heat is inconsistent — not absent, just unpredictable. We see this pattern on older DLGX gas models in Newport Beach and Thousand Oaks. Cost: $280–340 for coil replacement. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-gas-valve-replacement/">gas valve replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<h2>Three Checks You Can Do Before Calling</h2>
<p><strong>1. Check the exterior vent cap</strong> — go outside while the dryer runs and look at where the vent exhausts. The flap should be moving and you should feel warm airflow. Weak or no airflow means the vent is clogged.</p>
<p><strong>2. Check for d80/d90/d95 error codes</strong> — these confirm vent blockage. Note the exact code when you call us.</p>
<p><strong>3. Try timed dry instead of auto-dry</strong> — set the dryer to a specific 60-minute cycle. If clothes come out properly dry on timed mode but not on auto-dry, the moisture sensor needs cleaning, not a repair.</p>

<h2>When the Load Size Is the Problem</h2>
<p>A fully packed drum doesn't tumble properly — clothes stay compressed and hot air can't circulate through them. That's not a malfunction, just physics. If your dryer works fine on half-loads but struggles on large ones, try splitting them. But if even half-loads take 90+ minutes, something is mechanically wrong and we need to look at it. Also worth knowing: LG's steam and sensor-dry cycles run longer by design — 60–75 minutes is normal on those settings.</p>

<h2>What It Costs</h2>
<p>Depends entirely on the cause. Vent cleaning alone: $150–200. Moisture sensor cleaning: part of our diagnostic, no extra charge. Heating element: $300–380. Drum rollers: $280–350. Gas valve coils: $280–340. Most slow-drying calls run <strong>$180–380 total</strong>. The $65 diagnostic fee is waived when you approve any repair. Written quote after diagnosis — before we touch anything.</p>
<p>Is it worth fixing? On a dryer under 10 years old with a single failing component, almost always yes — a new LG dryer starts at $800 and that's before installation and haul-away. On an older machine where we find multiple things wearing out, we'll tell you that honestly on-site and let you decide. We'd rather give you the real picture than push a repair that doesn't make financial sense.</p>
