<h2>Questions We Get on These Calls</h2>

<h3>My LG dryer takes 2 hours to dry a load — what's wrong?</h3>
<p>First check: go outside and feel airflow at the exterior vent cap while the dryer runs. Weak or no airflow means the vent is clogged — that's the cause in about 70% of these calls. Second: check for d80, d90, or d95 codes on the display. Third: try switching to a timed 60-minute cycle — if clothes come out dry that way, the moisture sensor needs cleaning. Call us either way and we'll sort it out same day.</p>

<h3>How long should an LG dryer take to dry clothes?</h3>
<p>45–60 minutes for a full load on medium heat. Steam cycles and sensor-dry modes run 60–75 minutes by design — that's normal. If you're consistently hitting 90+ minutes or running two cycles, something needs attention.</p>

<h3>What are the d80, d90, d95 codes on my LG dryer?</h3>
<p>They indicate 80%, 90%, or 95% airflow restriction in the exhaust vent. Stop running heated cycles — a fully blocked vent will blow the thermal fuse and turn a slow-drying problem into a complete no-heat failure. Call us to clear the vent and test airflow properly.</p>

<h3>What is the moisture sensor and how do I clean it?</h3>
<p>Two metal bars inside the drum, usually near the front opening. Dryer sheet residue builds up on them and causes the auto-dry cycle to end early. Clean them with a cotton ball and rubbing alcohol every few months. If you can't find them, we'll show you when we're on-site.</p>

